Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. Certain columns, like cast and genres, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters. There are some odd characters in the cast column. The final two columns ending with _adj show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time. We will during evaluation of the data look at statistics such as mean, min and max values for the columns to understand the data.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

In this data analysis report, we will primarily focus our attention around the movie ratings and how those ratings relate to other variables. The report will be limited to aggregations and descriptive statistical graphs, and not dwelve into inferential statistics or machine learning concepts. We will look to answer the following two research questions:

  • How does genres relate to ratings? Are certain genres generally rated better?
  • Does it matter for the rating who is directing the movie and who the protagonist is?

Removing rows with a low vote count¶

A high vote count is preferred when analysing movie ratings as a low vote count can be more prone to bias. For example, say 15 students from a school class went to a cinema together, afterwards everyone rated the movie. Then, each view is likely to be influenced by the others in the group. The students in the class are also of the same age, and the culture may be the same. This is sample bias, and we are not looking at a random sample in this case. In IMDB, this phenomenon is typically seen right after movie releases. You will have few movie votes in the beginning, and then usually as the movie gets more reviews, the rating can stabilize at a lower level than what it was. Preferably we would like a rate count of say, at least 10.000, but in this dataset we will need to settle with less. We will first inspect the quantiles first, then decide on a threshold.

50% of the data falls below a vote count of 39. The trade-off here is that we need to remove movies with too few votes (as our independent variable is dependent on the number of votes), and still retain enough data for analysis. Removing 50% of the data is already quite a lot, so we decide this as our threshold.

Cast adjustment¶

The cast consists of multiple actors. As we are only interested in the main protagonist, we will extract that from this column and create a new column. It doesnt actually say anywhere in the dataset documentation that the protagonist is the first actor, but this is what should be the case. The most important actor comes first, and it is also the way IMDB is set up. We will confirm the result by inspecting the top 20 rated movies.

In [18]:
# Perform the string split and confirm the | with the remaining cast is removed

Our independent variable vote_average has a min of 2.9, a max of 8.8 and a mean of 6.1854. From the histogram we observe an almost normal distribution, but there are outliers on both ends, and it is slightly skewed to the left. Scores between 3 and 4 fall outside the lower whisker, while scores above ~8.1 falls above the upper whisker. It seems more common for movies to receieve really bad scores (Vote averages <4) than to receieve exceptionally good scores (8.2+) in our dataframe. This is also confirmed in our boxplot, with many outliers spotted outside our lower whisker. The majority of the movie rating scores fall in the range of 5 to 8, centered between 5.5 and 7. From the graph we can observe how most genres fall within a rating average of approximately ~6.0 and ~6.5. However, some genres score noticably higher than the sample average. This includes for example animation and documentary. On the other hand, certain genres underperform on average. This includes the Horror genre and the TV Movie genre. Before we started this statistic we had a feeling horror would score low on average, and the graph confirms our expectation. However, this does not mean every horror movie is bad (receieves a low rating). For interest sake, let's look at some well performing horror movies.

In [61]:
def dir_data(df): 
    '''Function which takes as input a dataframe and
    returns a bar chart with average vote for top & bottom 10 directors
    The data is filtered on directors having directed more than 5 movies'''
    
    director_votes = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby('director')['vote_average'].mean()).reset_index()
    director_df = pd.DataFrame(df.director.value_counts().reset_index())
    director_df = director_df.rename(columns = {'index': 'director', 'director': 'moviecount'})
    director_df = director_df.merge(director_votes, how= 'inner', on ='director')
    director_df.query('moviecount > 5', inplace=True)
    top10d = director_df.sort_values('vote_average', ascending=False).head(n=10)
    bot10d = director_df.sort_values('vote_average', ascending=False).tail(n=10)
    bot10d = director_df.sort_values('vote_average', ascending=True).head(n=10)
    combined = pd.concat([top10d, bot10d]).sort_values(by='vote_average', ascending=False)
    combined = combined.set_index('director')
    
    combined.plot(kind='bar'
              , y='vote_average'
             , ylabel='Average Rate'
             , ylim=[3,9]
             , figsize = [14,5]
             , legend = 'yes'
             , rot = 60
                 )
In [62]:
dir_data(df)

To create the graph, we first filter out any directors with less than 5 movies in the dataframe. This is to exclude directors with "pure luck" as you can call it, producing one really good (or bad) movie.

When we inspect the graph it gives us an impression of what the best and worst directors can achieve in terms of average vote scores across their directed movies. While the famous director Quentin Tarantino with his signature style movies have received an average score of ~7.5, Jason Friedberg on the other hand have an average of ~3.9. This definitely does not seem like a coincidence, but statistical inference will be outside the scope for this analysis.

Protagonists directing their own movies¶

Next we will have a look at the phenomenon where the protagonist is also the director of the movie. We will create one population where this is the case, and the other where it isnt, and compare the populations. Again, our main variable of interest will be the average vote score. Are the directors(protagonists) outcompeting movies where this isnt the case? Let's have a look.

We start off by inspecting the data. Clint Eastwood and Sylvester Stallone are famous for producing their own signature style movies. In both cases they are protagonists in their own movies. Next we will have a look at some statistical comparisons between the populations.

In [65]:
def plot_comparison(df):
    '''Takes as input a dataframe and returns two dataframes to 
    compute two histograms and two scatterplots, one for each population'''
    
    dirprot = df.query('director == protagonist')
    dirnprot = df.query('director != protagonist')
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(14,10))
    dirprot.plot(kind = 'hist', y='vote_average', ax=axes[0,0], title='Director == Protagonist')
    dirprot.plot(kind = 'scatter', x='release_year', y='vote_average', ax=axes[1,0], title='Director == Protagonist')
    dirnprot.plot(kind = 'hist', y='vote_average', ax=axes[0,1], title='Director != Protagonist')
    dirnprot.plot(kind = 'scatter', x='release_year', y='vote_average', ax=axes[1,1], title='Director != Protagonist')
    plt.show()
In [66]:
plot_comparison(df)

The histograms for both populations look similar, but the director==protagonist sample has fewer score-observations in the range ~6.3 to ~6.8. The sample also doesn't contain any scores below ~4.2. When it comes to the scatterplots, we first of all see fewer datapoints for the leftern plot which is to be expected, but we also spot something else. There seems to be a spike in director==protagonist movie productions from around 2008 and onwards. Score-wise these are all across the scale, but there is an impressive amount with a score > 7 in regards to the sample size. For the director != protagonist sample, data points are widely distributed, but one thing of note is that there were very few bad scores in the 60s and 70s. Let's have a look at a timeseries next.

In [69]:
def prot_timeseries(df): 
    '''Takes as input a dataframe and returns a timeseries plot
    with a timeseries for each population with the mean score per year'''
    
    dirprot = df.query('director == protagonist')
    dirnprot = df.query('director != protagonist')
    dirprot = pd.DataFrame(dirprot.groupby('release_year')['vote_average'].mean(numeric_only=True))
    dirnprot = pd.DataFrame(dirnprot.groupby('release_year')['vote_average'].mean(numeric_only=True))
    dircomb = dirnprot.merge(dirprot, how='left', on='release_year')
    dircomb = dircomb.rename(columns={'vote_average_x': 'Director != Protagonist', 'vote_average_y': 'Director == Protagonist'})
    
    dircomb.plot(kind='line'
                , figsize=[14,6]
                , title = 'Timeseries comparison of directors and protagonists'
                , xlabel = 'Release Year'
                , ylabel = 'Average Rating')
In [70]:
prot_timeseries(df)

Finally, we are comparing the development over time for these two samples. For the director==protagonist sample we have to keep in mind the sample size and thus the spikes between the years, but it still does give us an impression of the time-development of these movies. For the director!=protagonist sample we spot a negative trend from the 60s until today for the mean score, as was generally seen for the genres. From 1995 and onwards this sample seems to underperform in terms of score against the director==protagonist sample, except for the year of '08/'09.

Conclusions¶

In this section we will revisit our research questions.

How does genres relate to ratings? Are certain genres generally rated better? In our early exploratory analysis we observed vote distributions from 2.9 all the way up to 9. Some genres had a score centered in a smaller range, while others were quite spread out. From the descriptive statistics we found that the documentary genre was heavily outperforming other genres, while the horror genre was underperforming. Given the large sample we are working with, the sample average was something we could use to draw insights. However, this does not mean that any new observation falls within the score ranges for the genres. From the horror genre, there are also edge cases of very good movies. The documentary genre also had a minimum of 5.3, hence any genre can perform good or bad. That said, certain genres will statistically speaking, more often than not get a good rate. How this translates into the global population of movies is not possible to conclude from this analysis.

Does it matter for the rating who is directing the movie and who the protagonist is? We found from our descriptive analysis that it does matter who is directing the movie and who the protagonist is. When we compared the best and worst performing directors in terms of average score, we found that the difference is quite substantial. Quentin Tarantino had the highest average movie rating score (across all his movies) of 7.5, compared to the worst performing Jason Friedberg with a score of 3.9. Since this score is averaged across at least 5 movies, it gives us an indication of the quality these directors produce. This does not however exclude the chance of high performing directors producing bad movies in the future (or bad directors doing the opposite)! Confidence intervals or hypothesis testing would be fit to research this question even further.
For example we could extend the analysis with a 99% confidence interval for score ratings with corresponding intervals for the different directors. Perhaps for a future analysis.

Limitations: We stuck with data wrangling, exploratory data analysis and descriptive statistics in this report. It would be interesting to extend this analysis to inferential statistics or machine learning concepts to draw more insightful conclusions. Inferential statistics could include confidence intervals, hypothesis testing or regression analysis of scores. Statistical budget-score-revenue matching could also be of interest, and how adjusting one influences the other. Machine learning concepts could also be interesting, such as predicting the average score (y), based on features in the dataframe. Such machine learning can in practice be used to predict movie scores prior to releases. Perhaps even influence choice of directors or actors, or cast in general, as the production team is aiming for a good score. From a movie production point of view, perhaps budget and revenue would be of even higher importance, predicting revenue based on features in the dataframe. In a hypothetical scenario, you can extend this to an optimization problem, where you want to maximize the revenue (or profit) based on the other features.
